Introduction to Least-Square SVM Introduction Least Squares Support Vector Machine (LS-SVM) is a modified version of the traditional Support Vector Machine (SVM) that simplifies the quadratic optimization problem by using a \textit{least squares cost function}. LS-SVM transforms the quadratic programming problem in classical SVM into a set of linear equations, which are easier and faster to solve.
\subsection{Optimization Problem (Primal Problem)}
\begin{align*} &amp;\min_{w, b, e} \frac{1}{2} \lVert w\rVert^2 + \frac{\gamma}{2} \sum_{i=1}^N e_i^2,\ &amp;\text{subject to } y_i (w^T \phi(x_i) + b) = 1 - e_i, \ \forall i \end{align*} where: \begin{itemize} \item $w$ is the weight vector.
